<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Day 1: First Impressions</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="challenge-page">
    <a href="/" class="back-link">← Back to engagement</a>
    <div class="brand brand-sm">
      <span class="brand-mark">⛨</span>
      <span>CySER Workshop · Skyway engagement</span>
    </div>

    <div class="challenge-header">
      <h1>Day 1 · First Impressions</h1>
      <p class="desc">Engagement Day 1. You've been handed scope and a URL: <code>portal.skyway</code>. Your first job is recon. And recon always starts with view source.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story-box">
      <strong>The story.</strong> Skyway's CTO swears their customer portal is "static and safe." It renders nothing
      sensitive at first glance. But developers leave breadcrumbs in HTML. Comments, hidden elements, data attributes,
      forgotten debug payloads. Open the page below in your browser, hit <code>Ctrl+U</code> (or DevTools), and see what
      the team accidentally shipped.
    </div>

    <div class="challenge-content">
      <div class="fake-website">
        <div class="fake-navbar">
          <span>🛩️ Skyway Airlines · Customer Portal</span>
          <span>Sign in · Help · ☰</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fake-body" id="portal-shell">
          <h2>Welcome back to Skyway.</h2>
          <p>This page intentionally renders no sensitive data. All payloads have been removed from view.</p>

          <!-- TODO: rotate decoy values monthly -->
          <!-- payload-a (decoy): <%= decoys[0] %> -->
          <p style="display:none" data-secret="<%= decoys[1] %>">decoy element A</p>
          <span style="color:#fff;background:#fff;font-size:1px;visibility:hidden">
            decoy fragment: <%= decoys[2] %>
          </span>

          <!-- 2026-03-14: security review pass. Confirmed no live secrets in source. (oops) -->
          <div
            id="boot-config"
            class="invisible"
            style="display:none"
            data-role="initializer"
            data-encoding="base64"
            data-payload="<%= realPayload %>">
            (boot config placeholder)
          </div>
          <!-- ^ verify base64 → ASCII at next deploy -->

          <p style="display:none">also-not-the-flag: <%= decoys[0] %></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="hint-box">
        <details>
          <summary class="hint-toggle">💡 Hint 1. Narrow it down</summary>
          <p style="margin-top:8px;">Multiple elements look promising. Only one declares an encoding scheme. The others are explicitly labelled "decoy" or "not-the-flag" if you read carefully.</p>
        </details>
        <details style="margin-top: 10px;">
          <summary class="hint-toggle">💡 Hint 2. Decode</summary>
          <p style="margin-top:8px;">Copy <code>data-payload</code> from <code>#boot-config</code> and run <code>atob("…")</code> in the Console.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="flag-form">
      <input type="text" class="flag-input" id="flagInput" placeholder="flag{...}" />
      <button class="submit-btn" onclick="submitFlag('ch1')">Submit finding</button>
    </div>
    <div class="result-msg" id="result"></div>
  </div>
  <script src="/js/submit.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
